'''John Coppolella''' (born July 28, 1979) is a former American baseball front office executive who served as the [[general manager (baseball)|general manager]] of the [[Atlanta Braves]] of [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) from 2015 through 2017. Coppolella resigned as general manager of the Braves after he committed amateur signing infractions. MLB [[List of people banned from Major League Baseball|banned him for life]] as a result of those violations.

==Early life==
Coppolella was born on July 28, 1979, and is of Italian descent.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kahrl|first1=Christina|authorlink1=Christina Kahrl|title=MLB's 30 general managers ... who are they?|url=http://espn.go.com/mlb/story/_/page/wintermeetings15_GMs/a-breakdown-major-league-baseball-30-general-managers|accessdate=January 27, 2016|publisher=ESPN.com|date=December 4, 2015|archiveurl=http://espn.go.com/espn/print?id=14281094|archivedate=December 4, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Bowman|first1=Mark|title=Family at forefront of Coppolella's Christmas|url=http://m.braves.mlb.com/news/article/211977088/coppolella-eyes-family-time-at-christmas/|accessdate=December 24, 2016|publisher=MLB.com|date=December 23, 2016}}</ref> He graduated magna cum laude with a business management degree from the [[University of Notre Dame]].<ref name=gm>{{cite news|first1=Mark|last1=Bowman|url=http://m.braves.mlb.com/news/article/152659872|title=Braves name John Coppolella general manager|publisher=MLB.com|date=October 1, 2015|accessdate=October 1, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Ex-Braves GM John Coppolella permanently banned; team loses prospects|url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/21506598/ex-atlanta-braves-gm-john-coppolella-placed-mlb-banned-list-team-loses-prospects|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=22 November 2017}}</ref>

==Career==
Prior to graduating, Coppolella was offered and initially accepted a job at [[Intel]]. He chose to continue exploring opportunities in baseball, and ultimately turned Intel down for an internship with the [[New York Yankees]], working for the MLB team from 2000 through 2006.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bowman|first1=Mark|title=Coppolella's work ethic took him from intern to exec|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/100830088/john-coppolellas-work-ethic-took-him-from-yankees-intern-to-braves-executive|accessdate=October 3, 2015|publisher=MLB.com|date=November 7, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first1=Ian|last1=Morris|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/case-john-coppolella-braves-next-160003449.html|title=The case for John Coppolella as the Braves' next GM|date=September 23, 2014|publisher=SBNation|via=Yahoo! Sports|accessdate=October 1, 2015}}</ref> 

===Atlanta Braves===
In 2006, Coppolella joined the Braves as their director of baseball operations. He held that position until 2011, when he served as director of professional scouting. In 2012, Coppolella was promoted to assistant general manager. After [[Frank Wren]] was fired as the Braves' general manager after the 2014 season, [[John Hart (baseball)|John Hart]] took over as the president of baseball operations of the Braves,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/sports/hart-says-yes-to-braves-will-head-baseball-operati/nhqXt/|title=Hart says ‘yes’ to Braves, will head baseball operations|work=Atlanta Journal Constitution|first1=David|last1=O'Brien|accessdate=October 1, 2015}}</ref> with Coppolella heavily involved in the team's transactions,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/sports/baseball/hart-in-charge-but-braves-moves-have-coppolellas-f/njppq/|title=Braves’ moves have Coppolella’s fingerprints|work=Atlanta Journal Constitution|first1=Jeff|last1=Schultz|accessdate=October 1, 2015}}</ref> including the trades of [[Craig Kimbrel]] and [[Jason Heyward]]. The Braves announced on October 1, 2015, that Coppolella was promoted to general manager, and signed to a four-year contract.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cooper|first1=J.J.|title=Braves Promote John Coppolella To General Manager|url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/majors/braves-promote-john-coppolella-general-manager/|accessdate=October 4, 2015|work=Baseball America|date=October 1, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Braves promote John Coppolella to general manager|url=http://espn.go.com/mlb/story/_/id/13787316/atlanta-braves-promote-john-coppolella-general-manager|accessdate=October 4, 2015|agency=Associated Press|publisher=ESPN.com|date=October 1, 2015}}</ref> On October 2, 2017, Coppolella resigned his position as general manager, after [[Major League Baseball]] disclosed several infractions regarding the Braves' signings of international players.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bowman|first1=Mark|title=Coppolella resigns as Braves' general manager|url=http://m.braves.mlb.com/news/article/257175486/braves-general-manager-john-coppolella-resigns/|accessdate=October 3, 2017|publisher=MLB.com|date=October 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=John Coppolella resigns as MLB investigates whether Braves broke international signing rules|url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/20895709/john-coppolella-resigns-mlb-investigates-whether-atlanta-braves-broke-international-signing-rules|accessdate=October 3, 2017|publisher=ESPN.com|date=October 2, 2017}}</ref> On November 21, he was [[List of people banned from Major League Baseball|banned for life from baseball]] by MLB as a result of their investigation into the matter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/262279086/mlb-issues-braves-penalty-for-signings/|title=Braves penalized for int'l signing violations|work=mlb.com|date=November 21, 2017|accessdate=November 21, 2017}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Coppolella is married and has three children.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.baseballprospectus.com/chat/chat.php?chatId=868|title=Chat: John Coppolella|accessdate=January 27, 2016|work=Baseball Prospectus|date=August 26, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Bowman|first1=Mark|title=Coppolella discusses busy offseason in Q&A|url=http://m.braves.mlb.com/news/article/162856366/braves-gm-john-coppolella-discusses-offseason|accessdate=January 27, 2016|publisher=MLB.com|date=January 26, 2016}}</ref>

