'''League Park''' was a [[stadium]] in [[San Antonio, Texas]]. It was primarily used for [[baseball]] and was the home of [[Minor League Baseball|minor league]] [[San Antonio Bears]].
==History== The ballpark was used from 1923 through 1932.<ref name=Whisler>{{cite web |url=https://www.expressnews.com/150years/military-sports/article/Diamond-gems-History-of-baseball-in-S-A-runs-6071972.php |title=Diamond gems: History of baseball in S.A. runs deep |first=John |last=Whisler |newspaper=[[San Antonio Express-News]] |date=March 18, 2015 |accessdate=November 4, 2018}}</ref> It was located at East Josephine and Isleta streets near [[Brackenridge Park Golf Course]],<ref name=Whisler/> and had a capacity of 6,000 people.<ref name=Olivo/> It hosted its first night game on July 24, 1930, with 3,400 in attendance.{{cn|date=November 2018}} It burned down on June 18, 1932, after a fire started in the clubhouse.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25116701/fire_destroys_baseball_plant_at_san/ |title=Fire Destroys Baseball Plant at San Antonio |agency=[[United Press International|UP]] |newspaper=[[The Marshall News Messenger]] |location=[[Marshall, Texas]] |page=1 |date=June 19, 1932 |accessdate=November 4, 2018 |via=newspapers.com}}</ref>
League Park was used for [[spring training]] by the [[1924 Boston Red Sox season|Boston Red Sox]] in 1924,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25114937/ehmke_arrives_at_the_sox_camp/ |title=Ehmke Arrives at the Sox Camp |newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]] |page=11 |date=February 27, 1924 |accessdate=November 4, 2018 |via=newspapers.com}}</ref> and hosted [[Babe Ruth]] and the [[1930 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]] in a preseason game on March 31, 1930.<ref name=Olivo>{{cite web |url=https://www.mysanantonio.com/life/columnists/paula_allen/article/Paula-Allen-DiMaggio-Ruth-played-several-games-645575.php |title=Paula Allen: DiMaggio, Ruth played several games in S.A. |first=Benjamin |last=Olivo |website=mysanantonio.com |date=September 5, 2010 |accessdate=November 4, 2018}}</ref>
A different ballpark in San Antonio, Block Stadium, was used from 1913 through 1923; it was also known as "League Park" after 1915.<ref name=Whisler/>
==Sources== * "Baseball in the Lone Star State: Texas League's Greatest Hits," Tom Kayser and David King, [[Trinity University (Texas)#Trinity University Press|Trinity University Press]] 2005
